    "explanation": "<p>The wrong statement is Option A.  </p>\n<p>• In the presence of red phosphorus and HI, acetic acid undergoes decarboxylation to give methyl iodide (iodomethane), not ethyl iodide (iodoethane).  </p>\n<p>$$P + I_2 \\longrightarrow PI_3$$  </p>\n<p>$$CH_3COOH + PI_3 \\;\\xrightarrow{473\\text{K}}\\; CH_3I + CO_2 + H_3PO_3$$  </p>\n<p>• Options B, C and D are all correct:  </p>\n<p>– Acetic acid (pKa ≃ 4.75) is weaker than formic acid (pKa ≃ 3.75).  </p>\n<p>– It effervesces with NaHCO₃, releasing CO₂.  </p>\n<p>– It does not reduce Fehling’s solution.</p>",
